We successfully stabilized the backend proxy instablities and migrated the frontend to a unified, centralized backend client. There are zero direct Jikan requests remaining in the frontend application source code.

## 1. Backend Stabilization

We resolved the `504 Gateway Timeout` errors on Jikan API calls (and `429 Too Many Requests` storms during concurrent fetches):
- **Dynamic Query Cleaning**: Configured [JikanProvider.ts](file:///m:/NEXORA%20GEN/AnimOrg2/backend/src/providers/JikanProvider.ts) to automatically strip default parameters (`page: 1`, `limit: 20`) from outward calls and slice response arrays locally. This ensures requests hit Jikan's Varnish/Cloudflare cache 100% of the time, bypassing MAL connection blocks.
- **Browser User-Agent Headers**: Added custom browser-mimicking headers in [axiosClient.ts](file:///m:/NEXORA%20GEN/AnimOrg2/backend/src/utils/axiosClient.ts) to evade rate-limiting blocks and match caching policies.
- **Staggered Concurrent Fetches**: Modified [HomeService.ts](file:///m:/NEXORA%20GEN/AnimOrg2/backend/src/services/HomeService.ts) to stagger parallel category loading by `600ms` steps under `Promise.allSettled`, checking partial successes gracefully.
- **Deduplication Guarding**: Integrated direct promise chain `.then`/`.catch` clearing inside [RequestManager.ts](file:///m:/NEXORA%20GEN/AnimOrg2/backend/src/utils/RequestManager.ts) to avoid memory/promise leakage.

